  {
    "user": "U02E4DAQGSZ",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1741245568.065079",
    "client_msg_id": "45dba423-efe2-4c7c-a265-2e2cb8e82109",
    "text": "homogeneous coordinates, you actually needs more than a 3x3 because matrixes can't represent linear offsets.\n<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homogeneous_coordinates>\n\nso you pad a 3d coordinate with a 1 to make a 4d coordinate [x, y, x, 1]\n\nThat 1 gets uses as the offset in the resulting math.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1741225511.217169",
    "parent_user_id": "U0378MDUG1Y",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "MrKSR",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "homogeneous coordinates, you actually needs more than a 3x3 because matrixes can't represent linear offsets.\n"
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homogeneous_coordinates"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\nso you pad a 3d coordinate with a 1 to make a 4d coordinate [x, y, x, 1]\n\nThat 1 gets uses as the offset in the resulting math."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "channel_name": "present-company",
    "channel_id": "C01932BJGE8"
  },
  {
    "user": "U02E4DAQGSZ",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1741245889.169509",
    "edited": {
      "user": "U02E4DAQGSZ",
      "ts": "1741245948.000000"
    },
    "client_msg_id": "8252bac4-d9ed-4b82-8209-907488ea084c",
    "text": "<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camera_matrix>\n\nok for projection from a screen space to 3d space the homogeneous coordinates are the pixels, so from what you would naturally think of as a 2d coordinate becomes a 3d coordinate [x, y, 1], multiplied by the camera matrix.\n\nAfter you do math with homogeneous coordinates you often end with a vector that does not have a 1 in the last position, and you  have to normalize it (divide everything by the magnitude of the last element) to make the pixel parts usable",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1741225511.217169",
    "parent_user_id": "U0378MDUG1Y",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "BP+DV",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camera_matrix"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\nok for projection from a screen space to 3d space the homogeneous coordinates are the pixels, so from what you would naturally think of as a 2d coordinate becomes a 3d coordinate [x, y, 1], multiplied by the camera matrix.\n\nAfter you do math with homogeneous coordinates you often end with a vector that does not have a 1 in the last position, and you  have to normalize it (divide everything by the magnitude of the last element) to make the pixel parts usable"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "channel_name": "present-company",
    "channel_id": "C01932BJGE8"
  },
  {
    "user": "U02E4DAQGSZ",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1741246443.158049",
    "client_msg_id": "5f951b79-c2f0-4e02-8329-35da5c7be4dd",
    "text": "homogeneous coordinates are a critical trick in computer graphics/vision\n<https://www.tomdalling.com/blog/modern-opengl/explaining-homogenous-coordinates-and-projective-geometry/>\n\nIts something I would not think of myself but it transforms projective geometry (I assume thats what you are doing) into a linear space and makes all the matrix math work, which wouldn't the naive way.\n\nE.g. you _can't_ translate a 2d point with a 2x2 matrix, a 2x2 matrix center's rotations, scales and shears around the 0,0 point. So lots of trivial movement like panning the canvas cannot be represented.\n\nyou _can_ translate a [x, y, 1] point with a 3x3 matrix if you normalize it after. Thats the homogeneous coordinate trick that underpins pretty much all computer graphics.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1741225511.217169",
    "parent_user_id": "U0378MDUG1Y",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "G/trA",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "homogeneous coordinates are a critical trick in computer graphics/vision\n"
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://www.tomdalling.com/blog/modern-opengl/explaining-homogenous-coordinates-and-projective-geometry/"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\nIts something I would not think of myself but it transforms projective geometry (I assume thats what you are doing) into a linear space and makes all the matrix math work, which wouldn't the naive way.\n\nE.g. you "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "can't",
                "style": {
                  "italic": true
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " translate a 2d point with a 2x2 matrix, a 2x2 matrix center's rotations, scales and shears around the 0,0 point. So lots of trivial movement like panning the canvas cannot be represented.\n\nyou "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "can",
                "style": {
                  "italic": true
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " translate a [x, y, 1] point with a 3x3 matrix if you normalize it after. Thats the homogeneous coordinate trick that underpins pretty much all computer graphics."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "channel_name": "present-company",
    "channel_id": "C01932BJGE8"
  },
